segments.text: In January of 42, everything begins to get serious.
What did you and your classmates, who did you all think was going to win this war?
We had no doubt who was going to win the war.
The United States had never lost a war at that point.
I've always found today's students surprised
at that fact.
Many times I've had students say, but no, wait, y'all didn't, y'all weren't afraid.
I said, no, as far as I know, our generation knew who would win it.
We weren't, we didn't know how long it would take, but we knew what the outcome was going to be.
How soon did any of your close acquaintances leave for active duty?
None, as far as my close acquaintances did.
Not until we graduated.
And by and large, the student all went out.
What we did is we graduate on the 30th day of January, and then the following Monday, we all volunteered for enlistment.
And within
In one or two weeks, we were all either in the Army.
It was all Army then.
In this accelerated routine, did the Aggie routine of hazing and all that, did that change?
I suspect it did.
I pulled out a lot of that stuff.
I backed off.
I didn't like it.
I didn't mind being hazed myself.

I guess I might have been, but I didn't think that was a thing that we ought to do, and I pulled out, and spending a lot of time in the Longhorn office and things of that sort, I sort of disappeared from the
the long life times in the Corps itself.
I had friends, but I didn't take care of them.
I did accept the services of a freshman coming in and cleaning up the room.
And you lived on the campus those last three, two and a half years.
Two and a half years, right.
Let's see.
other wartime events that you remember hearing about them before you left the campus?
I was on the staff.
I was an associate editor of the Longhorn.
And in the process, if you look back at the 1943 Longhorn,

you will find that there were that medals were medal winners were generally portrayed and honored and featured within that and so it was in that particular process that we began to understand that Aggies were dying and that Aggies were caught and
People were out there fighting and it was then that I became very clearly aware, personally aware of the military and what was going on, battles that were going on.
Do you remember when you first had a personal acquaintance or member of the family who was wounded or killed in action?
Yes, I did.
I hear about it.
It wasn't any close family.
None of those were killed.
But people who were in Alney and in the church, I think, to the story you hear, have been lost.
And we felt it.
Let's see, I think I mentioned, any other events that you remember?
Let's see, because D-Day comes after you're already gone from here.
Oh, I know one.
Was Muster held in your undergraduate days on campus that you recall?
It must have been.
All right, your answer is about like everyone else's before the war.
I have the impression that muster was a low-key event until after the war, and the war made it much more meaningful.
The war made it much more meaningful, right.
And it was musters that you held when you were in the war, in the military, in the Imperial Hotel in Tokyo, for example.
There you go.
kinds of musters that you begin to remember.
When you graduated in January of 43, was there a final review?
There was a final review.
Held?
Yes.
Where?
In Drillfield.
Oh, okay.
Like all other forms.
Okay.
Do you have any idea who the reviewing officer was?
Was anybody notable?
No, as far as I know of, it was just the
And commencement was held where?
What family came for you?
My mother and father came.
They came.
My brother came.
No, I didn't.
Just my mother and father.
They were here.
I loaded up all the clothing I had when they left.
And I went back in the dormitory.
Founder of the room and stayed there until the next Monday.
And then you signed up?
Then I went to Houston and we all signed up.
At that point, how well prepared did you feel A&M had made you intellectually?
What did you, what was your opinion?
We had no question that we had one of the best educations that you could get.
We had no way of knowing, but we were confident in our education intellectually.
I thought it personally, I had a gated experience.

Having the kind of experience I had, not a leadership experience, but having taken the courses in veterinary medicine, having taken chemistry, having associated with Paul Pearson, being associated on the staff of the Longhorn.
And the only semester I did not distinguish was that last semester when I put in a lot of other time doing other things.
And by that time, was your goal to be a university faculty member?
Was that what you thought you wanted to be?
I don't know what I thought.
I came to Texas A&M to be a county agent.
All right, so when you left for the war,
That was another ball game.
I figured that when I came back, I talked to Pearson, I knew it, that I would come back at least for graduate work.
By the time I left, I think I was pretty clear that after this was all over, I was going to come back for graduate work.
After I came back from the war,
I had only one thing in mind, and that was to come back to Texas A&M and take a master's degree.
But you had not zeroed in, in 43, zeroed in on being a faculty member.
No.
A faculty member, my mother probably said that she thought that I would end up teaching at Texas A&M.
I never admitted it.
I sort of smiled when she said that, but that was her...
Let's see, back to some less important items.
Senior boots, where did you get yours?
Where everybody else got them.
Oh, so they were new ones?
They were new ones.
Remember what they cost?
No, I don't.
Somehow the figure $30 or so.
Did you keep them or did you pass them on?
I kept them for a while, and then somehow in the process they were lost.
So you didn't sell them to another?
I didn't.
What were the places of high living for a student when you were an undergraduate?
Where did students go to party?
Hard liquors?
Hard liquors.
Oh, okay.
Hard liquors.
Yesterday's Houston Chronicle had a big article about Aggies and other college students binge drinking.
Do you remember many Aggies drinking until they got drunk when you were an undergraduate?
I think everyone did during their career.
Is that right?
At least once or twice.
Okay.
Where did you all get the alcohol?
Well, it was beer.
Okay, where'd you get it?
I probably bought it at Hard Liquors.
At Hard Liquors, okay.
All right, what about whiskey?
You see, at that point, you could buy beer at Bryant.
Right.
Where did anybody get whiskey?
Well, that's another story, and I had to come from some distance.
Mm-hmm.
I've not heard anybody mention a bootlegger.
No, as far as I know, it was all beer.
Mm-hmm.
And... No hard whiskey, no hard drink at all.
It was strictly bitter.
And I've heard of a few after the war who would drive to Burleson County, to Whiskey Bridge, going to Snook, but I've not heard of anything before the war about much whiskey at all.
It wasn't until Burleson County, though it wept, and it could get over there that people went over and...

and bought their hard liquor drinks at that particular point when you were an undergraduate living in the core dorms was it common for a youngster to have beer in his room no i don't recall maybe one or two added but i don't recall anybody having beer in the dormitory as far as you were aware were there any places of ill repute in brazos county

anybody houses i've not heard of any and uh... now you went to look to lagrange uh... now when you went downtown brian there were three four movies downtown brian uh... and that wasn't a lot more fun apparently then going to movie on the campus
Were there other places downtown where Aggies would eat?
Yeah, you could find a place to eat down there.
There were several places.
I don't recall their names.
If your parents came to visit or any other relatives, where did you and they eat?
Well, we probably went to the Aggieland Inn to eat.
They're near Northgate.
Let's see.
Did you have any dates with Tessies while you were an undergraduate?
No, so you didn't have the routine of getting them here and so forth.
Let's see.
Let's see.
Tobacco.
How many students smoked and what did they smoke?
Oh, I smoked pipes and cigarettes.
Not cigars?
I don't recall.
How many did?
There were a number.
Half?
Half, maybe.
Was it okay to smoke in your room?
It was okay to smoke in the room.
Couldn't smoke in the dining hall?
No.
Did people dip snuff or chew tobacco?
Oh, yeah.
Especially in Animal Sun.
Oh, okay.
Were you even aware of other drugs or other things to smoke then?
No.
Did you know even the word?
I don't recall.
I don't recall even knowing anything.
Maybe I knew something about marijuana, but it was sort of something out in the distance that you just didn't touch that people did.
You weren't aware that anybody here ever?
No, I didn't know of anybody here.
Let's say back to football.
Describe any of those celebrity football players that were here your freshman year.
What was your impression of them?
Well, they were Kimbrough brothers.
What were they like as people?
They go to class.
They were students.
As a matter of fact, during the time that I was a student, I was a graduate student, the football team was in a corps right along with the student body, just sort of assembled.
So you had football players in your so-called outfit.
Now, when the athletes went to class, they wore their uniforms what?
Silver Taps, was it held when you were a student?
Yes.
Where?
The same place it was held now.
Was it similar in style and manner?
Similar in style, the same thing.
Using that, what are the events that unify Aggies in feelings?
The events, I'm not sure that there are, well, of course, Yale practice did.
Okay.
And the reviews, whether various and sundry times brought it in, of course, in the unifying situations.
But mostly it was within each organization and in the classroom.
It was in the classroom that you made your friends and carried on.
Was there... Because majors generally followed the same classes, they were in the same classes.
In terms of the way that you were accepted by your contemporaries,
and the way you accepted your contemporaries, was there much distinction of family income?
Absolutely not.
Absolutely not.
You didn't know what anybody made.
You knew that some people were gathering, you know, cleaning and turning it back and forth,
Did anybody... Did you just presume that they needed it?
But this was... You never looked down on them or anything?
I didn't see any, feel anything.
The uniform took away a lot of that kind of thing.
And the fact that you were Missouri Synod and somebody else was a Catholic or a Presbyterian?
That didn't make any difference either.
What about their last name?
I don't know that that made a difference.
Did you have some contemporaries that you knew that were... Well, you see, there were no blacks.
But there were Hispanic.
There were a few Hispanics, not many.
Were there any from other countries that you remember?
Not the undergraduate level.
No, they were people from particular South America.
That's what I thought.
And as far as you knew, were they accepted?
They were in the Corps.
And they were accepted like everybody else, weren't they?
Just like everybody else.
Now, Melvin Maltz, Houston, who comes after the war, I asked him about nicknames, and he said that he, being Jewish, was called Jew Boy.
And he said, I did not ever think of that as a put-down.
He said, in fact, I was proud to be Jewish.
Do you remember any incident of any sort?
Maybe, I don't know.
My nickname generally in the later years was Conker.
Kunk.
K-U-N-K. Just short of your name.
I didn't use the term Harry until long after.
Really?
Now, when you were growing up in Olney, were you Harry?
No, I was Harriet.
Harriet.
Okay.
And I presume that's Germanic?
Is that a German word?
I changed the spelling of it when I went into the military.
It changed from what to what?
From h-a-r-i-o-t to h-r-r-i-o-t. Because I know the double r. That's what I knew you as.
Let's see, oh, Bonfire.
Bonfire was Bonfire.
Where was it?
It was on the drill field.
And did you help ever?
Not really, no.
Not even as a freshman?
There were boxes that were put up there.
Okay.
There weren't any tree trucks?
No, no tree trucks or anything else.
What was usually up on the very top of it?
I don't recall.
There wasn't an outhouse?
There might have been.
Oh, okay.
Those were more after war.
Okay.
Let's see.
I have here Hollywood.
Was that after the war?
No.
The invasion of Hollywood came in in our senior year.
And the movie, as you well know, had never been licked.
And which...

They came in, and I was enough of around, I was with the core, with the Longhorn, so I, at that point in time, I met with some of the people that were talking about the early stages of the game, and planning our, the film, and then when they came in, and of course, here and there, I appeared in the movie.
How long were they here?
in the filming.
Two or three months.
Is that right?
Not very long.
And you people on the campus knew they were here, knew it was being filmed.
We were here and we used to watch the filming.
Where did they do most of the filming?
What parts of the campus did they capture most?
Well, they captured what was known as the President's House.
They captured, of course, Visa Hall.
They captured the area's military walk.
That area, they captured the area around the Claybrook Center, not the Claybrook, but the animal industry building there.
And did some of y'all try to maneuver yourselves into it?
Occasionally, to be seen in it, yes.
Who were the most notable stars that y'all saw?
Memory fails me.
Was Mitchum in that?
Robert Mitchum.
And he was here on the campus?
He was on the campus.
He played a secondary part.
Quine.
Richard Quine.
Yeah.
Who was the lady?
I don't remember.
I've got the movie at home.
I could look it up.
Okay.
Let's see, as you are preparing to leave the campus, you're getting ready to go to war.
How well did you feel you were prepared for that?
Well, I felt that I could do anything.
The first thing we knew we were going to do was we were the first class that came along that didn't have the summer camp, which justified commissioning right off on graduation.
We all had to go to Officer Kennedy School and had no particular problem going there.
How did your Aggie experience benefit you there at OCS compared to the others?
The rumor is
that after they lined it up, the class, this one class of which we had mostly Aggies in it, most of the Aggies were in this one class.
The rumor is that the military people, the officers, came up and as we, the first day they were there, they'd have people stand at attention and do the good old marine type of situation.
As I say, the rumor is that they all got drunk because the Aggies just stood up against them and didn't seem to bow or anything of this sort.
They didn't give in.
Now where was OCS for you?
Fort Sill.
Fort Sill, Oklahoma.
That is a rumor.
I don't know what it is, but at any rate, I don't know whether that was it or perhaps
Pretty easy time, you know, for a candidate school.
Aggie Ring, when did you, and how much did it cost?
When did you get your ring?
My ring cost me $28.
And when did I get it?
I got it the mid-semester of my junior year.
Okay.
And literally had to hide it until
All right, so because you were ahead in hours?
I was ahead in hours.
Okay, okay.
Do you have any stories of your Aggie ring down through the years?
I lost it once in a military restroom.
Went back and found it on the floor.
My, my.
During the war?
During the war.
My, my.
Where?
Do you remember?
Overseas?
Macon, Georgia.
Macon, Georgia.
My, my.
Do you still have it?
Oh, yes.
Any other stories about it?
No, none particularly.
Any where you were wearing it and somebody recognized it?
Oh, yes.
You always wore it.
You wore it during the military.
You took it overseas with you.
That was one thing that you kept.
I kept wearing it most of my life, except it got too... Then I transferred it to the right, and then I finally...
got too large and it kept falling off and I quit wearing it as a result of that.
Because I'm thinking that that's also one of those Aggie unifying features.
That is a graduate unifying.
There's no question about it.
The ring is the one that
And even today, with men and women, with a very small percentage of the student body being in the core, that ring is still the common unifying factor.
Curiously, I'd have it in the room.
I'd put it on at night when everybody was around.
Take it off.
Because I didn't dare wear it.
The seniors would object.
What are the qualities of being an Aggie?
I think the quality of being an Aggie is a good deal of self-confidence.
That somehow, I'm all right.
What I do is okay.
It lives with me.
I had no trouble with courses.
I had no trouble with studies.
I felt I could do anything except be a military leader or be elected.
And I think that's partly my personality that I had.
I was sort of a squeaky voice fellow.
I didn't gain my loud voice until I got
into the military itself, and had to, and somebody said, sound off.
There was also a, probably a kind of arrogance, too, that it was better.
You're saying...
Yeah, you're saying that it's more than just confidence.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
And they were confident that your education was first class.
Now, you must have known when you came, you must have known a few Aggie graduates.
Yes.
Do you now realize that you saw that kind of quality in them too, some of those qualities?
Yes, I think so.
That's the reason why I guess I came to A&M.
is that I came across those people that carried on that kind of confidence, knew them.
And you never thought about going anywhere else, transferring?
I did earlier, yes.
No, no, I mean once you enrolled here.
Once enrolled?
Oh, no.
No, I was most disappointed.
Joe Cole, who left the early part of us here and went to Texas Tech, I couldn't see.
I just said, you're going for an inferior education.
You just don't have any guts.
It takes guts to come around here and live here.
It takes a certain amount of courage.
All right, as you look back,
What did it mean to you, to your life, that you came to Texas A&M?
Well, I don't know that I ever questioned what it meant to me.
I accepted that I was a graduate of Texas A&M, and this opened certain doors for me.
I graduated immediately.
I went into the military and of course Aggies were respected in the military.
We were, it meant, I don't know.
which is sort of a part of life that you had.
You were there.
You were an Aggie, so... All right, I've got two other questions scheduled.
Did you hear anybody else say that?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
What have we not talked about about your student days that we should have?
Well, I told you I think about everything that I needed to.
